Note: ========================================
Note: WASM to HIR Translator
Note: ========================================
Note: Translates WebAssembly AST to High-level Intermediate Representation
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Preserves module structure, functions, types, and instructions
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/wasm/wasm_parser.runa" as Parser
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/dictionary.runa" as Dict
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_core.runa" as StringCore
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/string_primitive.runa" as StringPrim
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Note: WASM node type constants (must match wasm_parser.runa)
Constant WASM_MODULE as Integer is 1
Constant WASM_FUNCTION as Integer is 2
Constant WASM_PARAM as Integer is 3
Constant WASM_RESULT as Integer is 4
Constant WASM_LOCAL as Integer is 5
Constant WASM_INSTRUCTION as Integer is 6
Constant WASM_TYPE as Integer is 7
Constant WASM_IMPORT as Integer is 8
Constant WASM_EXPORT as Integer is 9

@Reasoning:
The top-level WAT (module ...) construct decomposes into four heterogeneous child kinds (functions, imports, exports, type declarations); enforcing that decomposition at the top of translation keeps downstream HIR consumers stable across input variants.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Build a Dictionary with type=wasm_module, optional module name from the node value, then iterate children dispatching by their node_type tag into four pre-allocated Lists. Attach the four Lists at keys functions / imports / exports / types.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in module-level child count; each child triggers an O(c) sub-translation where c is its own child count.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Operates on a parser-produced tree, but the parser itself trusts upstream WAT source; the input-tag check (WASM_MODULE) short-circuits on a non-module root to avoid misinterpretation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_wasm_to_hir" takes wasm_ast as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Main entry point - translate WASM AST to HIR dictionary

    If wasm_ast is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let hir be proc create from Dict

    Note: Set HIR document type
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "wasm_module"
    proc set from Dict with hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Get module node type and validate
    Let node_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wasm_ast, 0
    If node_type is not equal to WASM_MODULE:
        Return hir  Note: Not a module node, return empty HIR
    End If

    Note: Translate child nodes
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with wasm_ast, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    Note:
    Extract the optional module name. The parser stores the head keyword
    ("module") on the node value, so the symbolic module name - when present -
    is the first child and is recognisable by its leading '$'. Capturing it as
    "name" lets the backend re-emit "(module $name" identically.
    :End Note
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let first_child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Let first_is_name be proc child_is_dollar_name with first_child
        If first_is_name is equal to 1:
            Let mod_name_str be proc node_lexeme_string with first_child
            Let mod_name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
            proc set from Dict with hir, mod_name_key, mod_name_str
        End If
    End If

    Note: Create lists for different node types
    Let functions be proc create from List
    Let imports be proc create from List
    Let exports be proc create from List
    Let types be proc create from List

    Note: Process all children
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0

        Note:
        A module-level '$name' leaf carries the WASM_TYPE tag (the parser tags
        every bare leaf token that way) but is the module name, not a type
        declaration. Skip it so it is not mistranslated into a bogus type entry.
        :End Note
        Let is_name_leaf be proc child_is_dollar_name with child

        If child_type is equal to WASM_FUNCTION:
            Let func_hir be proc translate_function with child
            If func_hir is not equal to 0:
                proc push from List with functions, func_hir
            End If
        End If

        If child_type is equal to WASM_IMPORT:
            Let import_hir be proc translate_import with child
            If import_hir is not equal to 0:
                proc push from List with imports, import_hir
            End If
        End If

        If child_type is equal to WASM_EXPORT:
            Let export_hir be proc translate_export with child
            If export_hir is not equal to 0:
                proc push from List with exports, export_hir
            End If
        End If

        If child_type is equal to WASM_TYPE:
            If is_name_leaf is not equal to 1:
                Let type_hir be proc translate_type with child
                If type_hir is not equal to 0:
                    proc push from List with types, type_hir
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add collections to HIR
    Let funcs_key be proc create_string_literal with "functions"
    proc set from Dict with hir, funcs_key, functions

    Let imports_key be proc create_string_literal with "imports"
    proc set from Dict with hir, imports_key, imports

    Let exports_key be proc create_string_literal with "exports"
    proc set from Dict with hir, exports_key, exports

    Let types_key be proc create_string_literal with "types"
    proc set from Dict with hir, types_key, types

    Return hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
A WAT function bundles params, results, locals, and an instruction body; mapping each kind into its own HIR list keeps the resulting structure introspectable without re-walking the AST.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate a Dictionary tagged type=function. The parser stores the "func"
keyword on the node value, so the optional symbolic name is the first child when
it is a '$'-leaf; capture it at "name". Iterate the remaining children,
dispatching WASM_PARAM/RESULT/LOCAL into their translators and treating every
sub-sexpr that is not one of those structural keywords as a body instruction.
Attach the four Lists at keys parameters / results / locals / body.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) in the function's child count; nested-instruction operands incur their own translate_instruction cost.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "translate_function" takes func_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate WASM function node to HIR dictionary

    Let func_hir be proc create from Dict

    Note: Set type
    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "function"
    proc set from Dict with func_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Process function children (params, locals, results, instructions)
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with func_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    Note:
    Extract the optional function name: the first child, when it is a '$'-leaf,
    is the symbolic binding ($add). Record it and start the structural scan past
    it so the name is not mistaken for a body instruction.
    :End Note
    Let scan_start be 0
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let first_child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Let first_is_name be proc child_is_dollar_name with first_child
        If first_is_name is equal to 1:
            Let name_str be proc node_lexeme_string with first_child
            Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
            proc set from Dict with func_hir, name_key, name_str
            Set scan_start to 1
        End If
    End If

    Let params be proc create from List
    Let results be proc create from List
    Let locals be proc create from List
    Let body be proc create from List

    Let i be scan_start
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0

        If child_type is equal to WASM_PARAM:
            Let param_hir be proc translate_param with child
            If param_hir is not equal to 0:
                proc push from List with params, param_hir
            End If
        Otherwise:
            If child_type is equal to WASM_RESULT:
                Let result_hir be proc translate_result with child
                If result_hir is not equal to 0:
                    proc push from List with results, result_hir
                End If
            Otherwise:
                If child_type is equal to WASM_LOCAL:
                    Let local_hir be proc translate_local with child
                    If local_hir is not equal to 0:
                        proc push from List with locals, local_hir
                    End If
                Otherwise:
                    Note:
                    Any other sub-sexpr in a function body is an instruction -
                    folded forms like (i32.add (local.get $a) (i32.const 1)) and
                    flat forms like (return) alike. classify_head tagged them
                    WASM_INSTRUCTION (or, for heads named "type", WASM_TYPE if a
                    typeuse appears; those are skipped here as they carry no body
                    semantics for the round trip).
                    :End Note
                    If child_type is equal to WASM_INSTRUCTION:
                        Let instr_hir be proc translate_instruction with child
                        If instr_hir is not equal to 0:
                            proc push from List with body, instr_hir
                        End If
                    End If
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add function components to HIR
    Let params_key be proc create_string_literal with "parameters"
    proc set from Dict with func_hir, params_key, params

    Let results_key be proc create_string_literal with "results"
    proc set from Dict with func_hir, results_key, results

    Let locals_key be proc create_string_literal with "locals"
    proc set from Dict with func_hir, locals_key, locals

    Let body_key be proc create_string_literal with "body"
    proc set from Dict with func_hir, body_key, body

    Return func_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
WAT params are "(param $name? type)"; the optional $name lives on the param node itself while the value type is the first child token, and HIR preserves both for downstream signature reconstruction.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate a Dictionary tagged type=parameter. The parser stores the "param"
keyword on the node value, so the name and value type are both children: an
optional leading '$'-leaf is the name (stored at "name"), and the following leaf
is the i32/i64/f32/f64 value type (stored at "param_type").
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_param" takes param_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate function parameter to HIR

    Let param_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "parameter"
    proc set from Dict with param_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Children are [optional $name][value type]; split on the leading '$'.
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with param_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    Let type_index be 0
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let first_child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Let first_is_name be proc child_is_dollar_name with first_child
        If first_is_name is equal to 1:
            Let name_str be proc node_lexeme_string with first_child
            Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
            proc set from Dict with param_hir, name_key, name_str
            Set type_index to 1
        End If
    End If

    If type_index is less than child_count:
        Let type_child be proc get from List with children, type_index
        Let type_str be proc node_lexeme_string with type_child
        Let param_type_key be proc create_string_literal with "param_type"
        proc set from Dict with param_hir, param_type_key, type_str
    End If

    Return param_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
WAT results are unnamed value types (e.g. "(result i32)"); only the first child carries the type lexeme, so a single-child lookup suffices.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate a Dictionary tagged type=result. If the result node has at least one child, materialize the type token's lexeme into a String and store at "result_type".
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_result" takes result_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate function result to HIR

    Let result_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "result"
    proc set from Dict with result_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Get result type from children (result has no name; type is child 0).
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with result_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let type_child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Let type_str be proc node_lexeme_string with type_child
        Let result_type_key be proc create_string_literal with "result_type"
        proc set from Dict with result_hir, result_type_key, type_str
    End If

    Return result_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
WAT locals share the shape of params - optional $name followed by a value type - so the translation mirrors translate_param but emits a "local" tag and stores the type under "local_type".
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate a Dictionary tagged type=local. The parser stores the "local" keyword
on the node value, so name and value type are both children, mirroring
translate_param: an optional leading '$'-leaf is the name (stored at "name") and
the next leaf is the value type (stored at "local_type").
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_local" takes local_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate local variable to HIR

    Let local_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "local"
    proc set from Dict with local_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Children are [optional $name][value type]; split on the leading '$'.
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with local_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    Let type_index be 0
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let first_child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Let first_is_name be proc child_is_dollar_name with first_child
        If first_is_name is equal to 1:
            Let name_str be proc node_lexeme_string with first_child
            Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
            proc set from Dict with local_hir, name_key, name_str
            Set type_index to 1
        End If
    End If

    If type_index is less than child_count:
        Let type_child be proc get from List with children, type_index
        Let type_str be proc node_lexeme_string with type_child
        Let local_type_key be proc create_string_literal with "local_type"
        proc set from Dict with local_hir, local_type_key, type_str
    End If

    Return local_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
WAT instructions form folded expression trees - "(local.get $x)" or "(i32.add (i32.const 1) (i32.const 2))" - so nested instructions must recurse while leaf tokens (immediates, type tags) become operand dictionaries.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Store the opcode lexeme at "opcode". For each child: if its node_type is WASM_INSTRUCTION, recurse and push the nested Dictionary onto the operands list. Otherwise wrap the lexeme in a Dictionary tagged type=operand with the raw value at "value".
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) over the full subtree; recursion depth equals folded-instruction nesting.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Deep nesting can grow the call stack. Adversarial WAT should be reviewed for paren-depth at the parse stage before reaching translation.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_instruction" takes instr_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate WASM instruction to HIR

    Let instr_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "instruction"
    proc set from Dict with instr_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Extract instruction opcode/name (the head lexeme on the node value).
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instr_node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Let opcode_str be proc node_lexeme_string with instr_node
        Let opcode_key be proc create_string_literal with "opcode"
        proc set from Dict with instr_hir, opcode_key, opcode_str
    End If

    Note: Process instruction operands (nested instructions or immediate values)
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with instr_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let operands be proc create from List

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than child_count:
            Let child be proc get from List with children, i
            Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0

            If child_type is equal to WASM_INSTRUCTION:
                Note: Nested instruction
                Let nested_hir be proc translate_instruction with child
                If nested_hir is not equal to 0:
                    proc push from List with operands, nested_hir
                End If
            Otherwise:
                Note: Immediate value or type
                Let operand_str be proc node_lexeme_string with child

                Let operand_dict be proc create from Dict
                Let operand_type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
                Let operand_type_value be proc create_string_literal with "operand"
                proc set from Dict with operand_dict, operand_type_key, operand_type_value

                Let operand_value_key be proc create_string_literal with "value"
                proc set from Dict with operand_dict, operand_value_key, operand_str

                proc push from List with operands, operand_dict
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Let operands_key be proc create_string_literal with "operands"
        proc set from Dict with instr_hir, operands_key, operands
    End If

    Return instr_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
WAT imports have the form "(import "module" "name" desc...)"; positional children encode name first then descriptor, so positional dispatch is enough to lift them into structured HIR keys.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Build a Dictionary tagged type=import. The parser stores the "import" keyword on
the node value, so both the module string and the field name are quoted-string
children: child 0 -> "module", child 1 -> "name" (quotes stripped). The third
child is the import descriptor s-expression; its head lexeme (e.g. "func",
"memory", "global") is recorded at "descriptor" so the backend re-emits a
non-empty descriptor token. Additional children are ignored to mirror WAT's
grammar.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Import strings come from untrusted WAT source; downstream linkers must validate them before resolving module references.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_import" takes import_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate WASM import declaration to HIR

    Let import_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "import"
    proc set from Dict with import_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Process import children: "module" string, "name" string, descriptor.
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with import_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let module_child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Let module_str be proc child_string_literal_value with module_child
        Let module_key be proc create_string_literal with "module"
        proc set from Dict with import_hir, module_key, module_str
    End If

    If child_count is greater than 1:
        Let name_child be proc get from List with children, 1
        Let name_str be proc child_string_literal_value with name_child
        Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
        proc set from Dict with import_hir, name_key, name_str
    End If

    If child_count is greater than 2:
        Let desc_child be proc get from List with children, 2
        Let desc_str be proc node_lexeme_string with desc_child
        Let desc_key be proc create_string_literal with "descriptor"
        proc set from Dict with import_hir, desc_key, desc_str
    End If

    Return import_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
WAT exports are "(export "name" (kind $internal))"; the public name is stored on the export node itself while the first child carries the internal binding name.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocate a Dictionary tagged type=export. The parser stores the "export" keyword
on the node value, so the public name is the first quoted-string child (quotes
stripped, stored at "name"). The second child is the export descriptor, which on
the first emission is a folded "(func $internal)" s-expression and on a re-parse
of the backend's canonical "(export "name" $internal)" form is a bare
'$internal' leaf. extract_internal_name normalises both shapes to the bare
'$internal' lexeme so the round trip converges, storing it at "internal_name".
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Export names appear in module metadata; downstream embedders that surface them to dynamic linkers should validate UTF-8 well-formedness independently.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "translate_export" takes export_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate WASM export declaration to HIR

    Let export_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "export"
    proc set from Dict with export_hir, type_key, type_value

    Note: Process export children: public "name" string, then the descriptor.
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with export_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let name_child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Let name_str be proc child_string_literal_value with name_child
        Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
        proc set from Dict with export_hir, name_key, name_str
    End If

    If child_count is greater than 1:
        Let desc_child be proc get from List with children, 1
        Let internal_str be proc extract_internal_name with desc_child
        Let internal_key be proc create_string_literal with "internal_name"
        proc set from Dict with export_hir, internal_key, internal_str
    End If

    Return export_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
An export descriptor reaches translation in two shapes across a round trip: the
authored "(func $name)" folded s-expression on the first pass, and the backend's
canonical "(export "name" $name)" bare-leaf form on the second. Normalising both
to the bare '$name' lexeme is what makes generate_wasm_from_hir a fixed point on
exports: emit "(export "name" $name)" once, and every subsequent parse-emit
cycle reproduces it byte-stably at the structural level.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
If the descriptor node has no children it is already the bare '$name' leaf, so
return its lexeme directly. Otherwise it is a folded "(kind $name)" form whose
first '$'-leaf child carries the internal binding name; scan the children for
that leaf and return its lexeme. Falling back to the descriptor head lexeme keeps
the result non-empty for malformed descriptors that carry no '$'-leaf.
@End Implementation

Process called "extract_internal_name" takes desc_node as Integer returns Integer:
    If desc_node is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_string_literal with ""
    End If
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with desc_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    If child_count is equal to 0:
        Return proc node_lexeme_string with desc_node
    End If
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let is_name be proc child_is_dollar_name with child
        If is_name is equal to 1:
            Return proc node_lexeme_string with child
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return proc node_lexeme_string with desc_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
WAT type declarations bundle params and results into a reusable function signature; HIR splits them into parallel Lists of raw type strings to make the signature directly inspectable.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Dictionary tagged type=type_declaration. The parser stores the "type" keyword on
the node value, so the optional signature name is the leading '$'-leaf child
(stored at "name"). The signature itself lives inside a folded "(func ...)" child
whose WASM_PARAM / WASM_RESULT children each carry a value-type leaf. Collect
those value-type strings into the params / results Lists the backend expects, so
the emitted "(param T)" / "(result T)" forms carry concrete types rather than
the structural keyword.
@End Implementation

Process called "translate_type" takes type_node as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Translate WASM type declaration to HIR

    Let type_hir be proc create from Dict

    Let type_key be proc create_string_literal with "type"
    Let type_value be proc create_string_literal with "type_declaration"
    proc set from Dict with type_hir, type_key, type_value

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with type_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children

    Note: Optional signature name is the leading '$'-leaf.
    Let sig_start be 0
    If child_count is greater than 0:
        Let first_child be proc get from List with children, 0
        Let first_is_name be proc child_is_dollar_name with first_child
        If first_is_name is equal to 1:
            Let name_str be proc node_lexeme_string with first_child
            Let name_key be proc create_string_literal with "name"
            proc set from Dict with type_hir, name_key, name_str
            Set sig_start to 1
        End If
    End If

    Let params be proc create from List
    Let results be proc create from List

    Note:
    Collect param / result value types. They sit inside the folded "(func ...)"
    child of the type declaration, so descend into any WASM_FUNCTION child and
    read each WASM_PARAM / WASM_RESULT node's value-type leaf.
    :End Note
    Let i be sig_start
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0
        If child_type is equal to WASM_FUNCTION:
            proc collect_signature_types with child, params, results
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Let params_key be proc create_string_literal with "parameters"
    proc set from Dict with type_hir, params_key, params

    Let results_key be proc create_string_literal with "results"
    proc set from Dict with type_hir, results_key, results

    Return type_hir
End Process

@Reasoning:
A WAT function type's parameter and result value types live one level below the
"(func ...)" wrapper inside a "(type ...)" declaration. Factoring the descent
into a helper keeps translate_type readable and lets the value-type extraction
reuse the same name/type splitting logic the standalone param / local
translators use.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Walk the func node's children. For each WASM_PARAM, the value type is the leaf
after an optional '$'-name; for each WASM_RESULT, it is the single leaf. Append
each materialised value-type String to the corresponding List.
@End Implementation

Process called "collect_signature_types" takes func_node as Integer, params as Integer, results as Integer:
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with func_node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        Let child_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 0
        If child_type is equal to WASM_PARAM:
            Let p_str be proc value_type_of with child
            proc push from List with params, p_str
        End If
        If child_type is equal to WASM_RESULT:
            Let r_str be proc value_type_of with child
            proc push from List with results, r_str
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
A WAT "(param $x i32)" or "(result i32)" carries its value type as the final
leaf after an optional '$'-name. Extracting just that type leaf gives the raw
type string the type-declaration emitter and signature consumers expect.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the node's children; the value-type leaf is the last child when present.
Materialise its lexeme as a String, falling back to an empty literal when the
node has no children.
@End Implementation

Process called "value_type_of" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    If child_count is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_string_literal with ""
    End If
    Let last_index be child_count minus 1
    Let type_child be proc get from List with children, last_index
    Return proc node_lexeme_string with type_child
End Process

@Reasoning:
String-literal allocation is a single delegation but is wrapped here so that future changes to the canonical key-construction path (e.g., interning) only touch one call site.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Forward to StringCore.create_from_literal and return its pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_string_literal" takes value as String returns Integer:
    Return proc create_from_literal from StringCore with value
End Process

@Reasoning:
WasmNode lexemes are non-owning views into the source buffer (a pointer plus a
byte length). Translating a node into HIR requires materialising that view as a
heap String so the dictionary owns its own copy independent of the source
buffer's lifetime. Centralising the slice-to-String conversion keeps every
accessor consistent and routes through StringPrim, matching the sibling assembly
frontends.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Read the node's value pointer (offset 8) and length (offset 16). When the length
is positive, materialise the slice via StringPrim.string_substring with start 0
and the recorded length. A zero length yields an empty String literal so callers
can store the result without a null check.
@End Implementation

Process called "node_lexeme_string" takes node as Integer returns Integer:
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_string_literal with ""
    End If
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 16
    If value_length is greater than 0:
        Return proc string_substring from StringPrim with value_ptr, 0, value_length
    End If
    Return proc create_string_literal with ""
End Process

@Reasoning:
WAT symbolic identifiers begin with '$' ($add, $p, $x) while value-type tokens
(i32, f64) and quoted strings do not. Several translators need to tell whether a
leaf child is a name binding or a type token, and the leading '$' is the
unambiguous discriminator the lexer preserves in the lexeme bytes.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Inspect the first byte of the child's lexeme; return 1 when it is ASCII '$' (36)
and the lexeme is non-empty, 0 otherwise.
@End Implementation

Process called "child_is_dollar_name" takes child as Integer returns Integer:
    If child is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 16
    If value_length is less than 1:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let first_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with value_ptr, 0
    If first_byte is equal to 36:
        Return 1
    End If
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
WAT string literals are wrapped in double quotes in the source, and the lexer
preserves the surrounding quotes in the lexeme view. Import module / name fields
and export public names are quoted strings whose quotes must be stripped before
they become HIR String values, otherwise the backend re-quotes an already-quoted
token and the round trip drifts.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
When the child lexeme is at least two bytes and both the first and last bytes are
ASCII double-quote (34), materialise the interior span (offset 1, length minus 2)
as a String. Otherwise fall back to the full lexeme so non-quoted tokens pass
through unchanged.
@End Implementation

Process called "child_string_literal_value" takes child as Integer returns Integer:
    If child is equal to 0:
        Return proc create_string_literal with ""
    End If
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with child, 16
    If value_length is greater than or equal to 2:
        Let first_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with value_ptr, 0
        Let last_index be value_length minus 1
        Let last_byte be proc memory_get_byte from Layout with value_ptr, last_index
        If first_byte is equal to 34:
            If last_byte is equal to 34:
                Let inner_ptr be value_ptr plus 1
                Let inner_length be value_length minus 2
                Return proc string_substring from StringPrim with inner_ptr, 0, inner_length
            End If
        End If
    End If
    Return proc node_lexeme_string with child
End Process
